A Geroscience Perspective on COVID-19 Mortality.

Promislow DEL(1)(2).

Author information:
(1)Department of Pathology, University of Washington School of Medicine, 
Seattle.
(2)Department of Biology, University of Washington, Seattle.

A novel coronavirus, SARS-CoV-2, emerged in December 2019, leading within a few 
months to a global pandemic. COVID-19, the disease caused by this highly 
contagious virus, can have serious health consequences, though risks of 
complications are highly age-dependent. Rates of hospitalization and death are 
less than 0.1% in children, but increase to 10% or more in older people. 
Moreover, at all ages, men are more likely than women to suffer serious 
consequences from COVID-19. These patterns are familiar to the geroscience 
community. The effects of age and sex on mortality rates from COVID-19 mirror 
the effects of aging on almost all major causes of mortality. These similarities 
are explored here, and underscore the need to consider the role of basic 
biological mechanisms of aging on potential treatment and outcomes of COVID-19.

